etymologies: late 19th century; earliest use found in Alfred Wallace (1823–1913), naturalist, evolutionary theorist, and social critic. From phyllodin- (in scientific Latin Phyllodineae) + -ous

definitions: Having phyllodes; specifically of or relating to a subgenus or section Phyllodineae of the genus Acacia, found chiefly in Australia, most members of which have phyllodes.
